{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2024-01-03","name":"Cecily de Denton","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"Cecily de Denton","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Cecily"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"de Denton"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"alternateName":"Cecily Denton","gender":"Female","lifespan":"1242–1299","fullLifespan":"Abt 1242–Aft 1299","birthDate":"+1242","deathDate":"+1299","deathPlace":{"address":"Lancashire, England","geo":{"latitude":53.81849,"longitude":-2.62573,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"«b»Biography«/b»\n\"From a pleading of 1281 it appears that three years earlier William le Norreys had enfeoffed John de Byron of two-thirds of the manor of Heaton, and that John was put in seisin, but was ousted by Robert Grelley after three days; then John went to Robert's bailiff, claiming nothing except for a term of six years, and on the bailiff's refusal of entry, he went to Manchester to talk with Robert Grelley. He offered to surrender all his claim for 17 marks, and brought William le Norreys, who made a complete surrender of the manor to Robert Grelley, as to the chief lord of the fee. In 1281/2 an agreement was made between Grelley and Byron, the latter surrendered all his claim to two thirds of the manor, and acknowledged that he owed Robert £200 of silver. The other third was the dower of Cecily de Shoresworth (see Denton), and in 1283 Robert de Shoresworth and Cecily his wife appeared against Amadeus de Savoy and other guardians of the lands and heir of Robert Grelley, respecting her dower in 3½ oxgangs of land, water-mill, &c.\n\n\"Hawise, widow of Robert Grelley, claimed dower in this part of the manor; (where it is called Heaton next Wobrythe Bridge).\"\n\nBetween 1280 to 1299: \"To Richard, rector of Stockport, and his heirs Matthew de Reddish granted four oxgangs of land in Denton, that was to say a moiety of the vill, at a rent of 12d. Robert, rector of Mottram, no doubt an heir of Richard, granted all his land in Denton, namely two oxgangs, to his daughter Cecily, at 1d. rent to the grantor and 5d. to the lamp of St. Mary at Manchester.\n\nCecily was twice married: to a Norris of Heaton Norris and to Robert de Shoresworth.\n\n\"This Robert and Cecily his wife granted all their Denton lands, as well in demesne as in service, to their son William circa 1280. Later, in 1299, Cecily as widow of Robert modified the gift by granting half her father's land to her son Alexander and his heirs, with reversion to William.\"","events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1242","date":"Abt 1242"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1268","date":"1268","place":"Denton,Lancashire,England.","age":"26","id":"GFMG-VVW"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1270","date":"Abt 1270","place":"Lancashire, England","age":"28","id":"G9DF-2NQ"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1285","date":"1285","place":"Prestwich, Lancashire, England","age":"43","id":"G6TR-WCW"},{"name":"Death of Spouse","sources":"0","year":"1299","date":"Bef 1299","place":"Haslingden, Lancashire, England","age":"56","id":"L4BD-6ZP"},{"name":"Death","sources":"0","year":"1299","date":"Aft 1299","place":"Lancashire, England","age":"58"},{"name":"Marriage","sources":"0","type":"Spousal","id":"L4BD-6ZP"}],"parent":[{"name":"Alexander de Denton","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1215–1285","birthDate":"A+1215","deathDate":"+1285","age":70,"@type":"Person","identifier":"G6TR-WCW","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/G6TR-WCW/alexander-de-denton-1215-1285","published":true},{"name":"Alice Eccles","gender":"Female","lifespan":"1226–1268","birthDate":"+1226","deathDate":"+1268","age":42,"@type":"Person","identifier":"GFMG-VVW","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/GFMG-VVW/alice-eccles-1226-1268","published":true}],"sibling":[{"name":"Margaret de Denton","gender":"Female","lifespan":"1240–1310","birthDate":"+1240","deathDate":"+1310","age":