re, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Haslingden, Lancashire, England":"Haslingden, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1242–Aft 1299":"about 1242–after 1299","1240–1310":"1240–1310","1242–1299":"1242–1299","1235–1299":"1235–1299","1270–1363":"1270–1363","1215–1285":"1215–1285","1226–1268":"1226–1268","Aft 1299":"after 1299","1363":"1363","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1215":"1215","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","Bef 1299":"before 1299","1299":"1299","1310":"1310","Abt 1242":"about 1242","Abt 1270":"about 1270","Prestwich, Lancashire, England":"Prestwich, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Denton,Lancashire,England.":"Denton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Haslingden, Lancashire, England":"Haslingden, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Denton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places so called. The vast majority, including those in Cambridgeshire, Cumbria, Dumfries, Durham, Kent, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, Northumberland, Oxfordshire, Sussex, and Yorkshire are named from Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’ (see   Dean   1) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. An isolated example in Northamptonshire appears in the Domesday Book as <i>Dodintone</i> meaning ‘enclosure, settlement associated with <i>Dodda</i> or <i>Dudda</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Dean","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>dene</i> ‘valley’ (Old English <i>denu</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in various parts of England named Dean or Dene from this word.","English: nickname or occupational name for the servant of a dean or nickname for someone thought to resemble a dean. A dean was an ecclesiastical official, the head of a chapter of canons or a church official with jurisdiction over a sub-division of an archdeaconry. Though no doubt some deans had illegitimate children, they were officially celibate, and in the main the surname is probably a nickname in origin, similar to   Bishop  ,   Prior  ,   Priest  , and   Monk  . The Middle English word <i>deen</i>, <i>dien</i>, <i>dein</i>, is a borrowing of Old French <i>d(e)ien</i>, <i>doien</i> from Latin <i>decanus</i> (originally a leader of ten men, from <i>decem</i> ‘ten’), and thus is a cognate of   Deacon  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Deyne</i> (or <i>Dene</i>) a rhyming pet form of <i>Reynald</i> (see   Reginald  )."]}]},{"name":"Cecily","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecilie","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."]},{"name":"Cicely","meanings":["Variant of   Cecily .  This was a common form of the name in the Middle Ages, and in the 20th century was well known as the name of the British actress and singer  Cicely Courtneidge  (  1893–1980 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":17,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":48,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Cecily de Denton was born about 1242, her father, Alexander de Denton, was 29 and her mother, Alice Eccles, was 17. She married Robert de Shoresworth. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died after 1299, in Lancashire, England."},"et":{"Abt 1242–Aft 1299":"umbes 1242–pärast 1299","1240–1310":"1240–1310","1242–1299":"1242–1299","1235–1299":"1235–1299","1270–1363":"1270–1363","1215–1285":"1215–1285","1226–1268":"1226–1268","Aft 1299":"pärast 1299","1363":"1363","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1215":"1215","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","Bef 1299":"enne 1299","1299":"1299","1310":"1310","Abt 1242":"umbes 1242","Abt 1270":"umbes 1270","Prestwich, Lancashire, England":"Prestwich, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Denton,Lancashire,England.":"Denton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Haslingden, Lancashire, England":"Haslingden, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1242–Aft 1299":"noin 1242–1299 jälkeen","1240–1310":"1240–1310","1242–1299":"1242–1299","1235–1299":"1235–1299","1270–1363":"1270–1363","1215–1285":"1215–1285","1226–1268":"1226–1268","Aft 1299":"1299 jälkeen","1363":"1363","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1215":"1215","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","Bef 1299":"ennen vuotta 1299","1299":"1299","1310":"1310","Abt 1242":"noin 1242"